:"11 March 1483","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","28 December 1454":"28 December 1454","1425":"1425","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1464":"1464","1430":"1430","11 Mar 1483":"11 March 1483","South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, England":"South Ferriby, Lincolnshire, England","St. Paul's Cray, Kent, England":"St Paul's Cray, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","St Pauls Cray, Kent, England":"St Paul's Cray, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Craobhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Craobhach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘curly(-headed)’ or ‘prolific’ (from <i>craobh</i> ‘branch, bough’). Compare   Creevy  .","English: habitational name from Foots Cray, North Cray, Saint Mary Cray, Saint Paul's Cray, all in Kent and all named from the River Cray, which is named with a Celtic word meaning ‘fresh, clean’; or less likely from Cray in Buckden, Yorkshire, which is probably named with the same word.","Americanized form of German   Krey   and perhaps also   Kray  , and Dutch <b>Kraaij</b> or <b>Kraij</b> (see   Kraai  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Creagh","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Craobhach</b>, <b>Ó Craobhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Craobhach’</i>, a byname meaning ‘curly(-headed)’ or ‘prolific’ (from <i>craobh</i> ‘branch, bough’); see   Cray   1. This is an epithet of the O'Neills of Clare, one of whose ancestors is said to have carried a green branch into battle."]},{"name":"Creevy","meanings":["Irish (Westmeath): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Craobhaigh</b>, <b>Ó Craoibhe</b> ‘descendant of <i>Craobhach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘curly(-headed)’ or ‘prolific’ (from <i>craobh</i> ‘branch, bough’).","Irish and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Riabhaigh</b>, see   McGreevy  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":53,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alice Cray was born in 1402, in St Paul's Cray, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir John Fereby in 1430. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 11 March 1483, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 81."},"et":{"1402–11 March 1483":"1402–11. märts 1483","1380–1454":"1380–1454","1415–1483":"1415–1483","1425–1464":"1425–1464","1402–1483":"1402–1483","11 November 1464":"11. november 1464","Abt 1425":"umbes 1425","1483":"1483","11 March 1483":"11. märts 1483","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","28 December 1454":"28. detsember 1454","1425":"1425","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1464":"1464","1430":"1430","11 